<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910708-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>910708-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Heritage Savings Bank   Is Sold to Crestar Bank;   Offices Reopen Today</HL><DATE>07/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   CRFC UCTC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)SOUTHERN U.S. BANKS (BAS)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Heritage Savings Bank, Richmond, Va., wassold to Crestar Bank, and Heritage's 13 offices will reopenfor business today, the Resolution Trust Corp. announced.   Crestar, also based in Richmond, will assume all ofHeritage's deposits, which totaled $527 million, and will buy$625,000 of assets. Heritage had total assets of $582 millionand total liabilities of $638 million.</LP><TEXT>   The RTC will advance $526 million to Crestar and will tryto recover some of that money through the sale of assets fromthe failed institution. The agency expects the transaction tocost $194 million.   Separately, the deposits from the Colonia, N.J., branch ofColonial Federal Savings Association were transferred toUnited Counties Trust Co., Cranford, N.J. The insureddeposits for the other four branches of Colonial Federal,which was based in Roselle Park, N.J., will be paid off bythe RTC within the next few days.   Colonial Federal had total assets of $228 million andliabilities of $258.6 million, including $257.1 million indeposit accounts.</TEXT></DOC>